column20: Thank you for choosing to participate in this study. Please read the consent form belowPurpose:This survey investigates people’s perception of social relationships.Procedure:You are invited to compete a questionnaire consisting of about 100 questions and some demographic information questions.Risks and Side Effects:There is no risk or side effect.Benefits:?By completing this questionnaire, you will receive a monetary reward.Confidentiality:The results of this study may be published in an academic journal/book or used for teaching purposes, relevant scientific data may be shared to other researchers for further analysis. However, your name or other identifiers will not be used in any publication or teaching materials without your specific permission.Do you consent to participate in this study?
column21: In this survey you will be asked to rate relationships based on different bipolar scales. The entire survey should take about 10 minutes.?At the top of each page, there will be two phrases on opposite ends of the presented slider bars. Please move the slider toward the phrase you feel best relates to the presented relationships. Slidersautomatically start at one side of the bar and need to be moved, if only slightly, to register a response.?You will be presented with relationships throughout the survey, but the bipolar scales will change on eachpage. Please take into account all aspects of the relationships, including the way the two individuals in each relationship typically think and feel about each other, how they act and react toward each other, how they talk and listen to each other, and any other characteristics of the relationships that occur to you. It is important to consider the relationship as a whole and not just of one party's perspective.?Please answer each question carefully in order to have your assignment approved. There will be questions to test that you are taking the assignment seriously. If it is clear that you did not take this assignment seriously, it will not be approved and you will not receive payment for this assignment.

column38: "Valence" EvaluationDefinition: A relationship is ‘Cooperative’ if both people (a) have a common interest or goal, (b) like each other, (c) benefit from the relationship, (d) think alike or have similar views. Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Competitive’.Examples: ‘Cooperative/Friendly’ (e.g. between friends) vs ‘Competitive/Hostile’ (e.g. between competitors in sports)How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column65: "Socioemotional" EvaluationDefinition: A relationship is ‘Socioemotional’ if both people (a) interact socially based on personal and familial ties, or (b) are emotionally intimate and pleasure-oriented. Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Task-oriented/Intellectual’, which emphasizes more on business, service-wise, and occupational associations. Examples: ‘Socioemotional’ (e.g. between second-cousins, between lovers) vs ‘Task-oriented/Intellectual’ (e.g. teacher-students).How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column102: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). Examples: ‘Communal’ (e.g. husband-wife) vs ‘Exchange’ (e.g. prostitute-customer) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column111: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column129: "Concreteness" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Concrete’ if people exchange tangible resources (e.g. objects, products, services, money, and intimate behavior). Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Symbolic’ and people exchange intangible resources (e.g. respect, power, love, and information such as instruction, advice, and opinion). Examples: ‘Concrete’ (e.g. salesperson-customer) vs ‘Symbolic’ (e.g. politician-supporter) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column318: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). column327: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column543: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. column750: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). column759: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column966: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. column975: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1299: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1398: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). Examples: ‘Communal’ (e.g. husband-wife) vs ‘Exchange’ (e.g. prostitute-customer) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1515: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1722: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). column1731: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1938: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). Examples: ‘Communal’ (e.g. husband-wife) vs ‘Exchange’ (e.g. prostitute-customer) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column1947: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column2146: "Communal Sharing" EvaluationDefinition: People in a ‘Communal’ relationship willingly share resources (time, food, space) with each other. Benefits are given in support of the partner's welfare non-contingently? that is, benefits are given without the donor or the recipient feeling the recipient has an obligation to repay. In contrast, people in ‘Exchange’ relationship do not share resources for free. They have to follow some exchange rules—a benefit comes with a price tag and payback (e.g. money, time, service, resource). Examples: ‘Communal’ (e.g. husband-wife) vs ‘Exchange’ (e.g. prostitute-customer) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column2154: "Reciprocity" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Reciprocal’ if both people provide mutual, matched benefits to each other and follow some exchange rule of symmetry — receiving a benefit results in an obligation (debt) to return a comparable benefit. This relationship emphasizes on taking turns and getting equal shares (e.g. return favors, tit-for-tat, desire for equality, fairness, and balanced reciprocity). It is characterized by tit-for-tat provision of benefits between members, even balance and one-for-one correspondence, keep track of how far out of balance it is. Examples: ‘Reciprocal/Turn-taking’ (e.g. between coworkers) vs ‘Non-Reciprocal’ (e.g. celebrity-fans) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding

column2170: "Concreteness" EvaluationDefinition: The relationship is ‘Concrete’ if people exchange tangible resources (e.g. objects, products, services, money, and intimate behavior). Otherwise, the relationship is ‘Symbolic’ and people exchange intangible resources (e.g. respect, power, love, and information such as instruction, advice, and opinion). Examples: ‘Concrete’ (e.g. salesperson-customer) vs ‘Symbolic’ (e.g. politician-supporter) How well do you understand this dimension?-Level of understanding
